A vulnerability becomes more exploitable when multiple stages allow an attacker to prepare and execute malicious content systematically. In this case, the issue is a Stored XSS weakness. XSS allows attackers to inject client-side scripts into web pages viewed by users. When the attack is stored instead of reflected immediately, it persists across user interactions and can affect multiple people.

Stored XSS occurs when unsanitized input data is stored in a database or file system and later displayed without proper security checks. In this example, the review message is saved in the database and then rendered directly in the response. If no validation prevents malicious characters, an attacker can inject script elements. This becomes particularly problematic if the affected page runs JavaScript from the rendered content.

